<div id="review_80060655" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/80060655" />
    <a title="Marvin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2160536-marvin"><img alt="Marvin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1485672728p2/2160536.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/80060655?book_show_action=true">Dec 06, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Marvin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Marvin" href="/user/show/2160536-marvin">Marvin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2160536-marvin?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer80060655" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14739790070840904890">My second favorite novel of Thompson&apos;s after <i>Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas</i>. <i>Campaign Trail &apos;72</i> is the epitome of the gonzo journalism experience. The author has just the right amount of straight journalism and personal experience which of course includes some of his own outrageous reactions and opinions. The amazing thing is how much he got right. His predictions were pretty much correct. We now know that the Democrat Party really did sabotage the McGovern campaign and were fine with four years</span>
  <span id="freeText14739790070840904890" style="display:none">My second favorite novel of Thompson's after <i>Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas</i>. <i>Campaign Trail '72</i> is the epitome of the gonzo journalism experience. The author has just the right amount of straight journalism and personal experience which of course includes some of his own outrageous reactions and opinions. The amazing thing is how much he got right. His predictions were pretty much correct. We now know that the Democrat Party really did sabotage the McGovern campaign and were fine with four years of Nixon rather then allow a visionary that might rock their boat into the White House. Quite a few things in the books has Thompson's own prankish mark on them such as the strange accusation that Muskie was using drugs. (In a TV interview, Thompson stated something like "I was only reporting the rumors that were out there. I know because I'm the one who started them".) And I was never quite sure if Thompson really did interview McGovern while he was using the urinal. Yet this type of drama is what made Gonzo journalism what it was and, at least in Thompson's hand, existed to illuminate the truths that were hiding just behind the events.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14739790070840904890" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


